[
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110032\">@Reid Barton</span> was talking about potentially proving existence and properties of colimits in arbitrary \"equational theories\", which means that this stuff wouldn't have to be proved for each category individually. An important theorem is the theorem that the forgetful functor to <code>Set</code> preserves directed colimits.</p>\n<p>What is the general theorem that would give me the existence of things like colimits, but also free groups, rings etc. in these categories. Is it possible to have automation that would just prove the existence of something random like the free ring over an abelian group?</p>",
        "id": 191161654,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584645156
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Is it the adjoint functor theorem?</p>",
        "id": 191161774,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584645232
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Note that this is more than one theorem</p>",
        "id": 191161790,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584645242
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe. What does the adjoint functor theorem say?</p>",
        "id": 191161854,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584645257
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It says that under certain conditions, a functor has an adjoint, and when you apply it to the forgetful functor from Group to Set, the adjoint is the functor which sends a set to the free group on that set</p>",
        "id": 191161917,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584645293
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>although IIRC not every version of the adjoint functor theorem applies to that functor, because Group doesn't have a small generating set or something.</p>",
        "id": 191161996,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584645334
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have just read nlab very briefly. The condition is for being an adjoint, not for having an adjoint right? Or are these the same. Given a functor, I want to construct the adjoint, not just show the a functor I already have is the adjoint</p>",
        "id": 191162301,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584645456
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah I think these are the same. \"the adjoint\" of a functor actually means that you have two functors F and G, and F is a left adjoint of G and G is a right adjoint of F</p>",
        "id": 191162797,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584645710
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So I guess there is a theorem there to prove that all the forgetful functors between algebraic structures preserve colimits, and some other conditions that I don't properly understand. And then you can apply the adjoint functor theorem.</p>",
        "id": 191164037,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584646277
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But that's not true.</p>",
        "id": 191164077,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584646299
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For it to apply doesn't the forgetful functor from say <code>CommRing</code> to <code>Type</code> need to preserve colimits? Which it doesn't.</p>",
        "id": 191164441,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584646486
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The forgetful functor from CommRing to Type probably preserves limits</p>",
        "id": 191164616,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584646570
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so apparently it's a right adjoint</p>",
        "id": 191164655,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584646594
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>which means it has a left adjoint</p>",
        "id": 191164672,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584646605
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and this gives us a functor <code>F</code> from Type to CommRing which has some property which I'll have to look up</p>",
        "id": 191164720,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584646641
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see, I'm getting confused.</p>",
        "id": 191164723,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584646642
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm already confused</p>",
        "id": 191164744,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584646651
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So this might mean Hom_{ring}(F(S),R)=Hom_{set}(S,R)</p>",
        "id": 191164840,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584646702
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>where R is a ring which is regarded as a set on the RHS</p>",
        "id": 191164872,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584646725
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For me, it's \"obvious\" that a free group exists, because if I look at the axioms for a group, I can make them into an inductive relation in the way colimits are constructed in <code>algebra/category/Group/colimits</code></p>",
        "id": 191165195,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584646891
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I couldn't do that with say integral domains</p>",
        "id": 191165224,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584646908
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Because I can't make a constructor for <code>zero_ne_one</code>, or <code>eq_zero_or_eq_zero_of_mul_eq_zero</code></p>",
        "id": 191165338,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584646956
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does this have something to do with limits not being preserved or something?</p>",
        "id": 191165398,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584646988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What's the correct generality for the theorem that says the forgetful functor from Group or CommRing or Module to Set preserves directed colimits?</p>",
        "id": 191165791,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584647187
    },
