    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"270476\">@orlando</span> That's right. (But I think you mean \"preserve <em>colimit</em>\".)</p>",
        "id": 191172281,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1584650483
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok ... i flip limit and co-limit !!!! Thx !</p>",
        "id": 191173330,
        "sender_full_name": "orlando",
        "timestamp": 1584650964
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right -- the forgetful functor preserves limits (because to make a categorical product of rings you put a ring structure on the product of the underlying sets, and...probably something about subsets) and the free functor preserves colimits (a special case of which is precisely Orlando's statement)</p>",
        "id": 191173379,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584651000
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So integral domains and fields etc aren't equational theories I guess, and neither are topological spaces I suppose.</p>",
        "id": 191173541,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584651064
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The forgetful functor to set preserves filtered colimits I guess.</p>",
        "id": 191173600,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584651103
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/colimits.20in.20an.20arbitrary.20equational.20theory/near/191169752\" title=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/colimits.20in.20an.20arbitrary.20equational.20theory/near/191169752\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110044\">Chris Hughes</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/colimits.20in.20an.20arbitrary.20equational.20theory/near/191165195\" title=\"#narrow/stream/116395-maths/topic/colimits.20in.20an.20arbitrary.20equational.20theory/near/191165195\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>For me, it's \"obvious\" that a free group exists, because if I look at the axioms for a group, I can make them into an inductive relation in the way colimits are constructed in <code>algebra/category/Group/colimits</code></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This might be the proof of the adjoint functor theorem in some sense. Maybe <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110087\">Scott Morrison</span> or <span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110032\">Reid Barton</span> know what's going on?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think the thing about inductive relations is essentially the statement that the forgetful functor from Group to <code>[has_one] [has_mul] [has_inv]</code> is a right adjoint.</p>",
        "id": 191195656,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584668629
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So maybe the general theorem is that in equational theories, forgetting axioms is always a right adjoint functor.</p>",
        "id": 191196026,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584669126
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And then maybe you can combine it with theorems about adjoints and products of categories, to get things like monoid algebras.</p>",
        "id": 191196202,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584669431
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think this generalizes to universal algebras or varieties (anything with operations and equations but not disequalities like in a field)</p>",
        "id": 191196290,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1584669564
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Which is what you'd expect because there's no such thing as the free field over a ring or something.</p>",
        "id": 191196465,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1584669754
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The integers has a map to all fields and there's no initial object in the category of fields</p>",
        "id": 191207513,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1584687819
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To me this feels reminiscent of classifying toposes of algebraic (or other sorts) of theory (eg see <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Lawvere+theory#the_theory_of_groups\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Lawvere+theory#the_theory_of_groups\">this nlab article</a>), I will think more about this</p>",
        "id": 191348481,
        "sender_full_name": "Bhavik Mehta",
        "timestamp": 1584801268
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For existence of free things, I think you generally want to show that the category of say groups is (equivalent to) the category of algebras for a monad. In particular this holds for any algebraic theory that comes from a Lawvere theory / equational theory / operad / basically any universal algebra thing.</p>\n<p>In this case we call the forgetful functor <em>monadic</em>.</p>\n<p>Now there's a theorem that a monadic functor <code>U : A -&gt; C</code> creates any limits that <code>C</code> has, and any colimits that <code>C</code> has and the monad and its square preserve (see <a href=\"http://www.math.jhu.edu/~eriehl/context.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"http://www.math.jhu.edu/~eriehl/context.pdf\">http://www.math.jhu.edu/~eriehl/context.pdf</a> p.180). In particular if the monad is <em>finitary</em> (preserves filtered colimits) then <code>U</code> will also preserve filtered colimits - and it turns out that the monad you get from a Lawvere theory / equational theory / any appropriately finite universal algebra thing is finitary. The same thing probably holds for directed colimits, though I'm a bit confused about when you can substitute filtered and directed.</p>\n<p>This should deal with most of what you want to know about the forgetful functor to <code>Set</code>. I don't know as much about forgetful functors between other categories. In the case of the free ring over an abelian group you can use the fact that rings are monoids in the category of abelian groups, and so the forgetful functor <code>Ring -&gt; AbGrp</code> is monadic. This stuff is related to the theory of distributive laws. I don't know if you can always get something like that by dropping axioms from an equational theory though.</p>",
        "id": 191353218,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Read",
        "timestamp": 1584807338
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We have that monadic functors creates limits, and we almost have that they create any colimits that the monad preserves in mathlib already</p>",
