    {
        "content": "<p>One slightly different path that's worth considering is that if <code>U : A -&gt; C</code> is monadic and <code>C</code> is cocomplete (e.g. <code>Set</code>) then to show <code>A</code> is cocomplete you just need to show that <code>A</code> has coequalizers. This will get you coproducts that are definitionally fairly sensible.</p>\n<p>The finitary monad approach (at least by the proof I know) will get you coequalizers which are definitionally absolutely horrendous, so it's only likely to be worthwhile if explicitly constructing coequalizers is pretty hard for the category in question.</p>",
        "id": 191367767,
